    "description": "The strategy is a trend following tactical allocation on US equities that uses a dual moving average crossover on the S and P 500 ETF to define regime. When the 50 day simple moving average rises above the 200 day simple moving average, the model interprets this as a positive medium term trend and takes a full long position in SPY. When the 50 day simple moving average falls below the 200 day simple moving average, it treats this as a negative trend regime and flips to a full short position in S",
    "description_full": "The strategy is a trend following tactical allocation on US equities that uses a dual moving average crossover on the S and P 500 ETF to define regime. When the 50 day simple moving average rises above the 200 day simple moving average, the model interprets this as a positive medium term trend and takes a full long position in SPY. When the 50 day simple moving average falls below the 200 day simple moving average, it treats this as a negative trend regime and flips to a full short position in SPY, aiming to capture persistent directional moves while avoiding prolonged exposure against the prevailing trend.\n\nSignals are computed from daily closing prices with indicator warm up, and the portfolio is evaluated each trading day. Position sizing is binary and concentrated: 100 percent notional long or 100 percent notional short, with immediate reversals on crossovers and no explicit cash allocation, volatility targeting, stop loss, or drawdown control beyond the trend filter itself. The intended edge is time series momentum in broad equity index returns, monetized through slow moving regime shifts rather than high frequency trading.",
